# PART I — FOUNDATION

## 1. Cover & Positioning

This protocol trains **humans** as sovereign architects and **agents** as senior operators. It anchors “dream-like” model drift to **verifiable reality** (Inception *totem* metaphor): legacy OT, fragile APIs, and token spend all require explicit grounding, not plausible text.

## 2. Acknowledgement

Built on durable engineering practice and the need for systems that outlive their builders. This is not a static book: it is **Git-friendly**, **policy-versioned**, and **observable** so future teams can audit and repair agent behavior years later.

## 3. Initial Chapter — Reality Drift & Grounding

**Track 1 — Human Observer**  
Long-horizon agents (e.g., Modbus/PLC/SCADA) can enter a *dream layer*: internal consistency while real-world commands diverge (safety limits, cost, compliance). Root cause: weak grounding, thin protocols, missing independent checks. **Strategy:** totem checks, zones (e.g., IEC 62443-style separation), digital twins, immutable invariants, HITL for irreversible acts. **10-year view:** totem definitions and spin logs are first-class artifacts in repo and telemetry.

**Track 2 — Agentic Kernel**  
This kernel requires:

ATC (Authorization & Tool Contract) — completed before Totem Spin.
RA (Receipt Artifact) — emitted after every run, including denies.
CFA (Counterfactual Alternatives) — two alternatives with rejection reasons, produced after Decomposition. Per the global mandatory spec in the Foundation section.
Operational rule: no write to field / production without totem pass + policy allow + (where required) human token.

